<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-146-176  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 146 176.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  March 1989 v6 n2 p93(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Viruses and worms: What to do? (precautions against computerviruses and worms) (includes related articles with definitions ofelectronic infections and describing Japanese reactions tocomputer viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gruman, Galen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Nov 2, 1988, Internet worm attack that shut down 6,000computers and later unrelated attacks on Milnet have made thepublic aware of the insecurity of computers and the data theystore.andP;  The Computer Society and other professional associationshave recommended such penalties as public censure and criminalprosecution, and HR 55, a bill pending in the US Congress,toughens the 1986 Virus Abuse Act by allowing prosecution evenwhen there is no specific damage.andP;  The Defense Department'sComputer Emergency Response Team at the Software EngineeringInstitute in Pittsburgh will attempt to prepare for and to preventsuch attacks rather than simply react to crises.andP;  The DefenseDepartment does not expect to make major changes to Arpanet orMilnet because both are intended for the research community andthus are designed to be as open as possible.andP;  The industry'sreaction to the Internet attack is described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesSecurity SystemsData SecuritySoftware DesignInternet (Computer network)ARPANETAnalysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>